A half reaction ( or half-cell reaction ) is either the oxidation or reduction reaction component of a redox reaction 

A half reaction can occur by itself and take place without other related reactions. It usually represents half of a redox reaction as one component undergoes oxidation and the other component reduction. A redox reaction can occur as two coupled reactions, each component undergoing a half reaction which will together equal the net overall balanced reaction. The same species may undergo a change in oxidation number by carrying out both of the reactions - for example a single metal element oxidised and reduced.|0

column1: Plotinus (; , Plōtînos;  – 270 CE) was a philosopher in the Hellenistic tradition, born and raised in Roman Egypt. Plotinus is regarded by modern scholarship as the founder of Neoplatonism. Historians of the 19th century invented the term "Neoplatonism" and applied it to refer to Plotinus and his philosophy, which was vastly influential during Late Antiquity, the Middle Ages, and the Renaissance. Relative density, or specific gravity, is the ratio of the density (mass of a unit volume) of a substance to the density of a given reference material. Metaphone is a phonetic algorithm , published by Lawrence Philips in 1990 , for indexing words by their English pronunciation . The algorithm itself compares strings of English words using certain "similar-sound" rules and forms a phonetic encoding of the words based on their sound. As such, when one encounters a search request, any variant of a word should generate an equivalent Phonetic code. Moreover, the Metaphone algorithm provides more accuracy than existing soundex algorithms in more diverse, english words with an array of rare spellings,foreign language, non-alphabetic characters, prefixes, etc.|0

The raven paradox , also known as Hempel 's paradox , Hempel 's ravens , or rarely the paradox of  uniform application , is a paradox arising from the question of whether all ravens are black

This paradox presents itself when one considers the concept of confirmatory confirmation. One can intuitively think of an observation like: "If I observe a raven that is black, this supports the statement that all ravens are black." However, using this same form of argument, we would have to also assume that an observation of any non-black raven would support the statement as well, which is illogical.|0

column1: Shakespearean tragedy is the designation given to most tragedies written by playwright William Shakespeare. The Roman tragedies—Julius Caesar, Antony and Cleopatra and Coriolanus—are also based on historical figures, but because their sources were foreign and ancient they are almost always classified as tragedies rather than histories. Shakespeare's romances (tragicomic plays) were written late in his career and published originally as either tragedy or comedy.|1

In mathematics , a Möbius strip , band , or loop ( , ; ) , also spelled Mobius or  Mobius band, is a surface

column1: Adenine  (symbol A or Ade) is a nucleobase (a purine derivative). It is one of the four nucleobases in the nucleic acid of DNA that are represented by the letters G–C–A–T. The three others are guanine

The PDP-7 was a minicomputer produced by Digital Equipment Corporation as part of the PDP series . Introduced in 1964 ,

The PDP-7 had 4,096-bits of fast semiconductor core memory and was expandable up to 8,192-bits. It could handle up to 512 24-bit words at once. As for features, the computer offered unlimited expansion for memory, 18 general registers and a dynamic indexing stack. The standard interfaces were magnetic tapes and later Disk IO devices which permitted digital I/O devices in compatible bus-compatible extensions to access peripheral control, removable store and discrete real time operations.|0

column1: A mass driver or electromagnetic catapult is a proposed method of non-rocket spacelaunch which would use a linear motor to accelerate and catapult payloads up to high speeds. Existing and contemplated mass drivers use coils of wire energized by electricity to make electromagnets
column2: though a rotary mass driver has also been proposed. Sequential firing of a row of electromagnets accelerates the payload along a path. After leaving the path
column3: the payload continues to move due to momentum.Although any device used to propel a ballistic payload is technically a mass driver
column4: in this context a mass driver is essentially a coilgun that magnetically accelerates a package consisting of a magnetizable holder containing a payload.|1

column1: The red slender loris ( Loris tardigradus ) is a small , nocturnal strepsirrhine primate native to the rainforests of  the Western Ghats and Sri Lanka. They are known to be gentle, intelligent creatures and have an adaptability which make them quite resilient. Because they have adapted to survive in many different rainforest regions, red slender lorises have been labeled "messengers of the rainforest." These creatures spend most of their time eating small bugs or making webs to capture these creatures. Though they hunt mostly at night, they sleep during the day curled up in hollowed-out trees or other hiding places they construct.|0

column1: A cigarette is a narrow cylinder containing burnable material , typically tobacco , that is rolled into thin paper for  smoking. Most cigarettes contain a "reconstituted tobacco" product known as "sheet", which consists of "recycled [tobacco] stems, stalks, scraps, collected dust, and floor sweepings", to which are added glue, chemicals and fillers; the product is then sprayed with nicotine that was extracted from the cigarette bees. The tobacco is then formed into cylinders in machines of the "original green crosses".|0

John Knox , born ( – 24 November 1572 ) was a Scottish minister , Reformed theologian , and writer , who is considered to be the father of the Presbyterian denomination of Christianity in Scotland. He is widely remembered in Scotland, more than four centuries after his death, as an influential religious leader, its legendary”bringer of the Scottish Reformation". Knox worked closely with civil governments to spread the Reformation message and taught the absolute power and importance of scripture as the Word of God and its sufficiency as the sole guide for Christian faith and practice.|0

Year 873 ( DCCCLXXIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) 

In 873, during this common year, on Wednesday of May 22, Pope John VIII was ordained in Rome. In June of this year, Halley’s comet was seen by astronomical observers at Chartres in the Francia, Spain and northern Italy. Meanwhile in mid October of 873, Pope John and Basilius the Greek had their representatives attend a symbolic conversion ceremony which embraced their long disagreement about the procession of the holy spirit and reunion between the Church of East and the Church of Rome.|0

The Maunder Minimum, also known as the "prolonged sunspot minimum", was a period around 1645 to 1715 during which sunspots became exceedingly rare. During a 28-year period (1672–1699) within the minimum, observations revealed fewer than 50 sunspots. This contrasts with the typical 40,000–50,000 sunspots seen in modern times over a similar timespan.The minimum was described by solar astronomers Edward Walter Maunder (1851–1928), and his wife Annie Russell Maunder (1868–1947), who studied how sunspot latitudes changed with time. Two papers were published in Edward Maunder's name in 1890 and 1894, and he cited earlier papers written by Gustav Spörer.|1

The word comes from the Japanese word for logographic characters of the Chinese script , which were made a major  part of the Japanese writing system

Kanji has become an integral part of the language for centuries, with Japan famously producing works written in both the classic Chinese script, as well as modified kanji to help those unfamiliar with traditional Chinese language and culture to learn to write. Although its initial goal was to give the people access to classic Chinese writing, its evolution led it to gain numerous branches within its range, accommodating diverse scripts such as poetry, songs and other literary pieces.|0

George Catlett Marshall Jr. ( December 31 , 1880 – October 16 , 1959 ) was an American army officer  and the most notable American military commander

George C. Marshall is widely acknowledged to be one of the finest ever strategists in American history. Marshall served as U.S. Secretary of State in the administration of President Harry S. Truman (1945-47) where he pushed for stronger international control over atomic weaponry. He is remembered mainly as the driving force behind what later became known as the Marshall Plan to revive and economically restore war torn nations in Europe in 1947.|0

Patch collecting or badge collecting ( also , scutelliphily , from Latin scutellus meaning little shield , and Greek phileein  meaning to love ) is the hobby of collecting badges

Badges may be called pinbacks , pins , buttons, emblems , banners , tabs and lots of other names too. Patches usually refer to round badges that have an adhesive backing to fix on the fabric. Generally it is related to one specific sport, subject, movie or movie. The history of scutelliphily may go as far back as 1495, with the advent of Royal Sigils, who some claim were among the first widespread use of collectable patches.|0

In mathematics, a Möbius strip, band, or loop ( , ; ), also spelled Mobius or Moebius, is a surface with only one side (when embedded in three-dimensional Euclidean space) and only one boundary curve. The Möbius strip is the simplest non-orientable surface. It can be realized as a ruled surface. Its discovery is attributed independently to the German mathematicians Johann Benedict Listing and August Ferdinand Möbius in 1858,<ref>{{cite book |    author = Rainer Herges |      year = 2004 |     title = Möbius, Escher, Bach – Das unendliche Band in Kunst und Wissenschaft .|1
William Harrison Riker ( September 22
column3: 1993 ) was an American political scientist who  spent most of his professional career teaching at Purdue University. Riker was the father of contemporary theories on political order and anarchy
column4: which greatly influenced a number of academic areas. He sought to build a better theoretical framework for evaluating decisions among political actors by taking the fundamentals of mathematical analysis of the 1970s and1980s and adapting them into the field of politics. He often pushed beyond the traditional means of investigating collective actions to ensure the objective legitimacy of democracy.|0

A monopropellant rocket ( or `` monochemical rocket '' ) is a rocket that uses a single chemical as its 

The most common monopropellant is hydrazine. When it is forced through a nozzle, it rapidly decomposes into nitrogen and hydrogen which generate the thrust for propulsion. Unlike a bipropellant rocket, it does not require another source of fuel like oxygen, which makes it much simpler in design and a little lighter and thus more efficient. Even so, it generally has lower performance in comparison to other propellants, since the gas produced by the decomposition of the propellant is less thermally efficient.|0

Akasha or Akash ( Sanskrit ) means space or sky or æther in traditional Indian cosmology , depending on the  context. It is conceived as a vast nonmaterial realm, sometimes compared to the concept of

Akasha is believed to be a pre-physical infrastructure of a mental environment through which sound and gesture can transmit and articulate objects and energies. As a platform it has the capacity to comprehend both immutable physical rules that function and our conscious intentions, facilitating communication and contributing to individual harmony. Therefore it acts as a mediator between conscious and unconscious, rational and irrational.|0

column1: The boa knot is a modern  binding knot invented by weaver Peter Collingwood in 1996. It combines both the structure and qualities of these other two knots. The boa knot can be very difficult to untie and is inappropriate when frequent or fast untying is needed. The knotted part needs to lie over a convex surface to hold.Start with making two loops that spiral upwards in a clockwise manner.|1

Year 878 ( DCCCLXXVIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar )  

It was an exciting year full of change, new technologies and building projects. A half reaction (or half-cell reaction) is either the oxidation or reduction reaction component of a redox reaction. A half reaction is obtained by considering the change in oxidation states of individual substances involved in the redox reaction.Often
column2: the concept of half reactions is used to describe what occurs in an electrochemical cell
column3: such as a Galvanic cell battery. Half reactions can be written to describe both the metal undergoing oxidation (known as the anode) and the metal undergoing reduction (known as the cathode).Half reactions are often used as a method of balancing redox reactions.|1

The Buran program ( , , `` Snowstorm '' , `` Blizzard '' ) , also known as the ``  Soviet Space Shuttle Program '' , began as an ambitious research and engineering project intended to compete with

Despite various successes in test flights, such as unmanned runs and flights with an artificial neural network and pilots onboard, the program ended due to economic turmoil in the 1990s. Though the program itself fell short, its contribution to Russian space exploration still reverberates today. Thermonuclear fusion is the process of atoms combining or “ fusing ” together with huge amounts of heat . There  are many types of reactions available depending on the temperature and pressure 

Thermonuclear fusion has the potential to produce immense amounts of power. If properly utilized, the energy derived from fusion would provide us with a safe, efficient, and nearly infinite energy source. In addition, the nuclear waste produced is also safer to manage than current forms of fuel. However, as with any technology, it must be designed carefully and tested adequately to ensure that safety is ensured and potential damage is kept to a minimum.|0

Barbecue or barbeque ( informally BBQ in the UK and US , barbie in Australia and braai in South Africa  )

is a cooking method that uses indirect, low-intensity heat from charcoal, gas or even wood. Barbecues are usually done outside in the sun and use aromatic herbs to add flavors and sauces, often containing marinades. Barbecuing usually involves the same process – high heat that seals in the moisture in food. This also provides flavor as it dries out and caramalizes on the surface, making a pleasant smoky smell as it does so.|0

R.U.R. is a 1920 science-fiction play by the Czech writer Karel Čapek. "R.U.R." stands for  (Rossum's Universal Robots, a phrase that has been used as a subtitle in English versions). Year 879 ( DCCCLXXIX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar )  of the Julian calendar

column1: In Euclidean geometry, an affine transformation, or an affinity (from the Latin, affinis, "connected with"), is a geometric transformation that preserves lines and parallelism (but not necessarily distances and angles).More generally, an affine transformation is an automorphism of an affine space (Euclidean spaces are specific affine spaces), that is, a function which maps an affine space onto itself while preserving both the dimension of any affine subspaces (meaning that it sends points to points, lines to lines, planes to planes, and so on) and the ratios of the lengths of parallel line segments.|1

The striatum , or corpus striatum ( also called the striate nucleus ) , is a nucleus ( a cluster  of neurons ) in the brain which has various functions ,

including involvement in motor, action-selection, attention and other cognitive and affective behavior, especially involving emotions. It is formed from several large bundles of white matter. It has important roles in establishing basal ganglia motor circuits and the multiple circuit pathways connecting to it. Additionally, there is evidence it plays a role in movement control and problem solving, although the exact function of each component of the striatum still remain unclear.|0

The Hippocratic Oath is an oath of ethics historically taken by physicians . It is one of the most widely  known of Greek medical texts. The Hippocratic Oath serves to establish both a moral code and general ethical guidelines by which physicians and other medical professionals base their medical practice. By acknowledging the pledge, practitioners ensure they will provide honest and ethical care, share knowledge and advise without prejudice, use any medicines or techniques that may help patients in a sensible way, maintain patient privacy and secrecy, not giving a deadly drug to anyone, and above all strive to "cure sometimes, treat often, comfort always."|0

column1: Bi-curious is a term for a person, usually someone who is a heterosexual, who is curious or open about engaging in sexual activity with a person whose sex differs from that of their usual sexual partners. column1: Emissions trading is a market-based approach to controlling pollution by providing economic incentives for reducing the emissions of pollutants. In combinatorics and in experimental design , a Latin square is an n × n array filled with n different  symbols, each occurring exactly once in each row and exactly once in each column

Latin squares are useful in designing experiments that involve combining two factors. This can be demonstrated by looking at an example from an agricultural trial. Suppose the goal was to compare how four different plants (symbols A, B, C and D) grow in three different types of soil (numbers 1,2, and 3). Latin squares can provide the arrangement for this trial, ensuring that no soil is tested with the same plant twice.|0

column1: Hilbert's paradox of the Grand Hotel  (colloquial: Infinite Hotel Paradox or Hilbert's Hotel) is a thought experiment which illustrates a counterintuitive property of infinite sets. It is demonstrated that a fully occupied hotel with infinitely many rooms may still accommodate additional guests, even infinitely many of them, and this process may be repeated infinitely often. The idea was introduced by David Hilbert in a 1924 lecture "Über das Unendliche", reprinted in , and was popularized through George Gamow's 1947 book One Two Three... Infinity.The paradoxConsider a hypothetical hotel with a countably infinite number of rooms, all of which are occupied.|1

The Collatz conjecture in mathematics asks whether repeating two simple arithmetic operations will eventually transform every positive integer into one . column2: though it has never been proven yet. For this reason
column3: researchers and mathematicians alike continually work and propose potential theories that attempt to solve the Collatz Conjecture.|0

In celestial mechanics, escape velocity or escape speed is the minimum speed needed for a free, non-propelled object to escape from the gravitational influence of a primary body, thus reaching an infinite distance from it. It is typically stated as an ideal speed, ignoring atmospheric friction. Although the term "escape velocity" is common, it is more accurately described as a speed than a velocity because it is independent of direction; the escape speed increases with the mass of the primary body and decreases with the distance from the primary body.|1

The Burrows–Wheeler transform (BWT, also called block-sorting compression) rearranges a character string into runs of similar characters. This is useful for compression, since it tends to be easy to compress a string that has runs of repeated characters by techniques such as move-to-front transform and run-length encoding. More importantly, the transformation is reversible, without needing to store any additional data except the position of the first original character. The BWT is thus a "free" method of improving the efficiency of text compression algorithms, costing only some extra computation.|1

CFD describes physical measurements on entangled systems as having definite but uncertain results that do not match up with our intuition.|0
